{What is here, in your opinion, the best move for Black? Black's turn.} 1... h5
{Black have very nicely placed pieces and with h5 he wants to stop White from
advancing on the king-side.} 2. N3h2 {White needs to defend his g4 pawn for a
moment.} hxg4 3. hxg4 Qc8 {Black wants to take the pawn on g4.} 4. f3 {White
defends it!} (4. g5 {This is not a good move because Black will open the
position on the king-side and White will not have enough pieces in the defense.
} Nh7 5. Qh5 g6 6. Qh4 f6 {Now Black opens the position and it is much better!}
7. gxf6 Nxf6 8. Nf3 Rf7 {Rook can go to h7 and all Black pieces can attack the
white King, which is without of any defense.}) 4... Nh7 {This is a very nice
move that stops White from advancing of the g pawn and prepares the trading of
the worst Black's piece for the best piece of White - the darksquared Bishop.}
5. Ng3 Bg5 {This is the idea.} 6. Nf5 {A very nice move! White attacks d6 pawn
and covers some of the bad squares on the king-side.} Qd8 {Black doesn't allow
Nd6, because of Qb6!} 7. Kg2 {White wants to take the h file. How Black needs
to proceed? Best Black's plan is to play g6 in order to get the white Knight
out of f5 and after that to move the King to g7. It is also possible to get
with the Rook from f8 to h8 and after this to prepare the strong idea of
playing on the dark squares. Qf6 maybe to f4 and so on...} (7. Nxd6 Qb6 $17)
7... g6 8. Ng3 Kg7 9. Rh1 Rh8 10. Nhf1 Qf6 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. Nxe3 {Now you can
see how Black plan works perfectly. After occupying dark squares Black will
aslo be a little bit better.} Ng5 13. Qe2 Rag8 14. Raf1 Qf4 {Black occupied
dark squares and he has a better position. Here black economically exchanges
darksquared Bishops and bring all of his pieces on perfect suares not only for
the defense but also for the offense.} *

