{The White's idea is to play h4 and open h file for the attack on the black
King. How Black can defend it? Black's turn.} 1... Bh4 {The main idea of White
is to play h4 and h5 in order to oppen the h file for the attack. With Bh4
Black stops this and also wants to exchange the great white darksquared Bishop.
} 2. Bg3 {White doesn't want to trade this Bishop, and he plays this move
because Black cannot take the Bishop because it will open the h file.} N8g7 {
Black very economically brings his pieces in to the play. The idea is to cover
the squares on f5 and h5 and after exchanging of the Knight on e6 the other
black Knight can come to his position.} 3. Qd2 Re8 {A nice defensive and
attacking move. Black brings the Rook on the half open e file and for a moment
alows the Knight, if it will be necessery, to come on f8.} 4. Qe1 {A nice
attacking move. White needs to attack Black. With Qe1 White wants to open the
h file eventually.} Bf6 {Another nice move. Black retreat with the Bishop and
prepares that piece for the defense of the dark squares around his King (g7
and h8) .} 5. Qf2 Qe7 6. h4 {White attack.} Nxf4 {One more very nice defensive
move. Black take attacking piece on f4, after whitch  he will bring other
Knight to e6 and the Bishop will stay on this vital defensive diagonal.} 7.
Bxf4 Ne6 8. g5 Nxf4 9. Nxf4 Bg7 {Now you can see the point. Black perfectly
cover all the squares around the king with the darksquared Bishop and now can
use other pieces for even attack on the white King on the queen-side.} 10. Rde1
Qd6 {The next move will be c5 and black is better. His King is perfectly safe
and it is very hard for White to organize attack on the black King.} *

